INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_category`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`) VALUES
(3, 1, '2005-09-29 16:59:28', '2005-09-29 15:59:28', 'They say that admiting a problem is the first major step to finding a solution, so here goes......  \r\n\r\n<strong><i>I am a functional addict</i>.  My poisons are alcohol and tobacco.</strong>\r\n\r\nWhat am I looking for?  I am looking for contentment.  Contentment, not happiness?  In my opinion, there are four facets to human happiness and these are the physical, the emotional, the mental and the spiritual.  I hesitate to use the word â€˜happinessâ€™ in my words because the word has been highjacked to convince us in various ways to buy, vote, think and other actions which will result in our happiness.  When you think happiness, what do you think of?  Contentment better describes the end goal of my journey.\r\n\r\nThe balance between these four aspects of the human being is what determines the overall well-being or contentment of the individual.  I suppose it is possible, to a certain extend, to compensate for a weakness in one of the facets.  In fact, nature does it for us sometimes as in the case of the better hearing of blind persons.  I do not believe that being more physical can solve a huge emotional problem.  What matters is the balance.\r\n\r\nAn imbalance is one aspect leads to imbalances in the other aspects of the human nature.  If you are unhealthy, then you are likely to be depressed (emotional) about it, which means that you may not be thinking (mental) properly.  The idea is where the balance is disturbed; you take steps to correct that problem.  I more inclined, at present, to believe that you have to balance the facet that is the cause of the problem.  For example, if you are spiritually void, it is the spiritual aspect that needs to be addressed.\r\n\r\n<strong>Physical:</strong>  Being basically healthy is good for you everyone knows that, I think.  Taking exercise, eating well and sleeping well are all good for you. The physical relates to you as a physical being, the stuff you can touch.\r\n\r\nYou might argue that mental and emotional states are the same as they are seen to be centered around the brain.  Furthermore, it could be argued that â€˜spitualismâ€™ is another aspect of emotion.  I beg to differ.\r\n\r\n<strong>Mental: </strong> The mental part of you relates to the way your brain works.  It is not about intelligence at all.  I mean who is more intelligent in the Kalahari desert, the San man (bushman) who can survive with very little or you?  The mental aspect is about making your brain work, about thinking about issues and trying to solve the daily grind of survival.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, the  <strong>â€˜emotionalâ€™</strong> aspect is about feelings; love, hate and all the sentiments in-between.  The emotional aspect is the hardest one to control but the other three parts affect it more readily.  If you are healthy, spiritually stable and mentally agile, you are more likely to have better control over your feelings.  I would go so far as to say that being in a good mood would help any lovemaking you do.  Negative sentiments are usually the result of other deep seeded insecurities that the person has.  A jealous husband may think that the wife knows that shortcoming and is looking for something better.\r\n\r\nTo make this clear, I do not believe in God.  At least not what the churches have been preaching for centuries.  If you believe in God, congratulations, this aspect of your life is being looked after and I know many people who are comfortable with their â€˜religionâ€™.  Religion, however, is only a means of expressing spirituality.  <strong>Spirituality</strong> is about believing, knowing, having faith in something we cannot physically, mentally or emotionally prove to others or ourselves.  It is a way of regarding the meaning of life, the reason for our existence and provides the moral grounding on which we base our lives.  I am now of the opinion, that just having an opinion of â€˜lifeâ€™ is inadequate.  Just being â€˜atheistâ€™ can be spiritual. If you do not examine and practice this spiritually regularly, you are spiritually poor. \r\n\r\nMy journey here is to find the right balance for me here and it has to start with handling and dealing with those things that keep me from starting and continuing.\r\n\r\nLove and peace, may you find the balance.\r\n', 'About this blog', 0, '', 'static', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'about-this-blogpod', '', '', '2005-10-04 19:47:31', '2005-10-04 18:47:31', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/blog/?page_id=3', 1),
(4, 1, '2005-10-01 19:59:13', '2005-10-01 18:59:13', 'I became aware of my problem some months ago.  At first I kept it to myself and tries a number of times to change the this habit I seem to have picked up.  It has not worked.  I have since mentioned the problem to a number of people close to me but most of them have not really taken it seriously probably thinking I was being melodramatic. <!--more-->I think I know why, but that is a later post.  My wife is now becoming very aware of the issue.\n\nI am talking about alcohol here.  I fear alcohol more so because my father was an alcoholic.  A real one.  However, my father''s alcohol problems caught up with him a few years after my birth and he ended up in mental hospital for the next 21 years before he died and so he had no influence on my drinking habits.\n  \nI do not drink when it is not appropriate.  I rarely drink at lunchtime, I work my hours and I do my household chores like everyone else.  Basically, I am still functional.  But provide the opportunity, like after work or during the weekend, and that can of lager will make an appearance sooner or later and I know once I have one drink, then the game is on.  Even I know that is not a sign of healthy drinking.  \n\nIs it possible that my realisation is a sign that there not really a problem, after all, I am not under any major pressure to admit it?  If that is the case, then why is it bothering me?  Am I being melodramatic?  Maybe, but if one is not happy with one''s self, it must be a duty to change that what makes you unhappy but is that possible, I mean, can you change your character by sheer will power? Do I have the will power to change this because no matter how I look at it, I like drinking, I like the socialising.  Stopping drinking completely will change all that, my friends and family all drink as a social activity.  I will look and feel like a prat if I refuse to drink when everyone else is.  After all, I have noticed that holding a conversation with someone who''s had a few whilst dry usually is not a conversation!   The problems of the world have been solved in many of these get togethers.\n\nI have to find out if this situation I find myself in is a symptom of a deeper problem that I cannot identify yet. ', 'Facing Reality', 0, 'I became aware of my problems some months ago.  At first I kept it to myself and tries a number of times to change the this habit I seem to have picked up.  It has not worked.  I have since mentioned the problem to a number of people close to me but most of them I told have not really taken in seriously probably thinking I was being melodramatic. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '4', '', '', '2005-10-12 21:32:43', '2005-10-12 20:32:43', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/blog/?p=4', 0),
(5, 1, '2005-10-02 20:13:39', '2005-10-02 19:13:39', 'Thinking back, throughout  my life, I have been exposed to drinking.  Mum ran a guest house in the Seychelles for over six years and I saw a lot of alcohol abuse (other''s) during those years.  I had my first drink at the age of 15 in the Seychelles but I do not remeber drinking again after that.  When we returned to Zimbabwe at age about 17, I started drinking more regularly, as my all my peers did.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nWhen I worked in a casino as a croupier after leaving school  in a Zimbabwean tourist resort that was totally boring out of season, I spent a lot of  time drinking with work mates and other off-season workers due to the unsociable hours we worked.  Hell, we even had serious drinking games!  My return to the capital did not change those habits.  Every man I knew enjoyed a jar or two or three.   Those late teen years were something else, the pubs and the nightclubs, the girls and the barbeques just had to enjoyed with beer.\r\n\r\nBeing an ambitious young man with a new family, I used my British citizenship to emigrate to the UK.  Emigrating is one of the hardest things I have done.  Assimilating to the new environment was very difficult but  without a social circle and the sheer lack of funds, drinking was occasional  and mostly controlled.    I came to learn computing but things did not work out as planned.  The family kept growing and things were hard for quite a few years.  \r\n\r\nThat has changed obviously and I suppose now that I am more comfortable,  was getting financial better off, have made friends and created a social circle that does now include more drinking.  This past year or so, my old drinking culture is returning with a vengence.  Up to this point, I do not believe I had an alcohol issue. \r\n\r\nSo what?  Well, I have found myself drinking more frequently (actually on a daily basis) and actually looking forward to it under the guise of socialising and once I get a taste then I find it difficult to stop until I have had a few.  I need to take time to analyse where it changed.\r\n', 'Alcoholic History', 0, 'Thinking back, throughout  my life, I have been exposed to drinking.  Mum ran a guest house in the Seychelles for over six years and I saw a lot of alcohol abuse (other''s) during those years.  I had my first drink at the age of 15 in the Seychelles but I do not remeber drinking again after that. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'alcoholic-history', '', '', '2005-10-12 21:34:00', '2005-10-12 20:34:00', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/blog/?p=5', 0),
(6, 1, '2005-10-03 20:44:35', '2005-10-03 19:44:35', 'I seem to have lost control of my drinking in the recent past.  Trying to justify it, I am more inclined to think it happened when I got DVT.  The doctors have never told me how I got it but I suspect I could have been one of the first ''computer related'' DVT victims.  <!--more-->A few months later,  I saw a story in the <a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/2698119.stm">news</a>  about the condition.  That may not be entirely true though because I was doing a lot of physical work in the garden in the same period so it could have been that.  I was doing a lot of long hours in front of the computer as the company I was working for at the time had a lot of things going.  It put money in my pocket and beer in my hand!\r\n\r\nThe DVT treatment lasted one year and it was the scariest time of my life.  The thought that a tiny blood clot could kill me at any time meant I spent countless hours in the hospital whenever I thought there was a problem.  I remember crying (I mean tears here) so many times, I wrote letters to my family to be opened in case of my demise, I hinted to friends and family to look after my kids etc.   I believe that is why some of them think I am being melodramatic now. \r\n\r\nI was taking blood thinning tablets  throughout this period but someone made the mistake of telling me that alcohol also thins the blood.  The tablet phamplet did not mention alcohol as being detrimental and I was as sure as hell going to ensure that my blood stayed thin.  I went evey week to have it checked and many a time it was not as thin as it should have been!  The drinking kept me sane and kept my blood thin.\r\n\r\nTowards the end of the year, I felt that both the GP and the hospital were starting to see me as a pest.  I had to insist that they do a scan on both legs to confirm that my DVT had gone.  I had to, no-one could explain why I still occassionally, as I do now, still have these pains in my calf.  One thing I do know is that during that period and after I have never felt so unhealthy in my life.\r\n\r\nI just wonder could it be this period that pushed me to build a dependance on the warm glow of alcohol?', 'When did it happen?', 0, 'I seem to have lost control of my drinking in the recent past.  Trying to justify it, I am more inclined to think it happened when I got DVT.  The doctors have never told me how I got it but I suspect I could have been one of the first ''computer related'' DVT victims. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'when-did-it-happen', '', '', '2005-10-12 21:35:43', '2005-10-12 20:35:43', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/blog/index.php/archives/6', 0),
(7, 1, '2005-10-04 22:00:07', '2005-10-04 21:00:07', 'My period of feeling unhealthy after the DVT saga was emphasised when my doctor suggested I should lose weight and I underestimated my weight in front of my work colleagues.  Some story on the BBC news site about BMI (Body Mass Index) was the pivotal point.<!--more-->  I came home that evening and weighed myself to be shocked at 104kgs. (I don''t do pounds or stones, I was educated to the metric standard).  At 180cms high (no feet and inches either) I was just about obese!  Maybe that would explain why I felt so unhealthy.  A bit of winding from my colleagues and I set about to find a plan, maybe like the one I plan now.\r\n\r\nThen I caught chicken pox and did get it bad, even the GP drew her breath when she saw me.  Mum always said I have had chicken pox but she had said that about my brother who had it about two years earlier.  How would she have known anyway, both of us where stuck in some bush boarding school at the normal age when kids get it?  For four years or so, she only saw us at Christmas.  Lots of kids at school, I remember, had chicken pox and even German measles but I don''t remember having it.  I got chicken pox from my son, the last born, after my three elder children all had a bout.  Did I catch it because I was unhealthy at the time?  I didn''t feel very stressed about the chicken pox but it did knock me out for a while.  The upshot was when it was all over I was 98kgs.\r\n\r\nI started to exercise to keep my weight going in the right direction for a while.  I discovered Tai-bo (fight like routines) and pilates.   I also re-discovered my love for swimming.  I am an early riser and so I did my exercise in the mornings (alternating pilates and Tai-bo) and finished with a 20mins swim.  It played havoc with my familyâ€™s and my morning routine and the swimming had to go a few weeks later.  A few weeks later and nothing was gone, I was still hovering round the 98kg mark.  It was then I knew I was going to have to diet as well.  I canâ€™t remember particularly any change in my drinking habits then, so it suggests, it was business as usual.\r\n', 'Obese Exercise', 0, 'Some story on the BBC news site about BMI (Body Mass Index) was the pivotal point.  I came home that evening and weighed myself to be shocked at 104kgs. (I don''t do pounds or stones, I was educated to the metric standard).  At 180cms high (no feet and inches either) I was just about obese!  Maybe that would explain why I felt so unhealthy.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'low-carbing-diet', '', '', '2005-10-12 21:36:55', '2005-10-12 20:36:55', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/blog/index.php/archives/7', 0),
(8, 1, '2005-10-05 22:59:18', '2005-10-05 21:59:18', 'Few weeks of non success leads to the contemplation of another â€˜planâ€™.  At the time there was a few articles about the â€˜Atkins dietâ€™.  Now I am not the type of person who takes things at face value and since I was in the process of thinking about loss weight and diets, I had a look and I was nearly convinced.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nWhy do I love the idea of low carb?  It has something to do with my African upbringing I suppose.  Meat, meat, fish, nuts, berries, fruit, vegetables and meat just made sense based on what I believe the human body has evolved to digest.  And water.  (Can you tell I love meat?)\r\n\r\nA few things put me off the Atkins diet and other low carb diets I discover in my research.  \r\n* counting of carbs â€“ I believe you should eat until satisfied.  If you eat the right food, should it matter? \r\n* supplements  - if you need supplements to complement your diet, then you are not eating well.\r\n* what have been described as â€˜pretend carbohydratesâ€™ obviously gracefully supplied by Atkins Inc. If you need to pretend to eat chocolate or whatever, then you might as well join the â€˜functional addictâ€™ club!\r\n* forcing your body to go onto fat eating mode, lipolysis and ketosis.  If you eat right, then, do you need to do this?\r\n \r\nBy far the most common sense low carb variation is one evangelised by a British man, David Mills with his carbWiser plan (<a href="http://www.low-carbdiet.co.uk/">http://www.carbwiser.com/</a>).  It is that plan with my variations that I followed for over the next 8 or so months.  My guiding principle with my diet was simple, if you cannot eat it raw or itâ€™s just sweet for nothing, donâ€™t eat it.\r\n\r\nI went from 98kgs in Sept 03 to at my lowest of 89kgs in Apr 04, some 9kgs in 7 months!  I also joined the brilliant forum at <a href="http://www.low-carbdiet.co.uk/">http://www.low-carbdiet.co.uk/</a>.   During this time I kept my exercise routine going and soon I put on some weight from muscle mass I expect.  I am now about 93 kgs but wearing size 36 trousers as opposed to 44 when I started.  Using clothes sizes is a better measure than weight because muscle is denser than fat.\r\n\r\nBut the devil drink had other ideas.  Beer always featured in my diet.  Slowly the exercise routines faded away, especially after Christmas and more rubbish food returned to my diet.  I still try and avoid some foods or limit my intake of rubbish food and that may suggest the reason for the slow weight gain being experienced now. \r\n', 'Atkins and Low Carb', 0, 'Few weeks of non success leads to the contemplation of another â€˜planâ€™.  At the time there was a few articles about the â€˜Atkins dietâ€™.  Now I am not the type of person who takes things at face value and since I was in the process of thinking about loss weight and diets, I had a look and I was nearly convinced.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '8', '', '', '2005-10-12 21:38:22', '2005-10-12 20:38:22', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/blog/index.php/archives/8', 0),
(9, 1, '2005-10-06 09:09:41', '2005-10-06 08:09:41', 'I suppose that the common view is that alcoholics drink until they fall over.  Is it true?  Can at least functional alcoholics have certain limits, because I seem to?<!--more-->\r\n\r\nI seem to have a normal upper limit of 6 to 8 pints of lager.  I do, on quite a few occasions, have more than this especially where the drinking period is extended for example at parties.  What seems to be the factor that sort of stops me is tiredness.  My normal bedtime is between 10pm and midnight and once sleeps calls; drink is out of the window.  By this time, I am not normally blind drunk and many times feel fairly sober.  In fact, I canâ€™t think of a recent occasion where I was very drunk.\r\n\r\nWhat seems to be one of the governing factor of whether I feel drunk or not is the pace at which I consume the alcohol.  My normal routine is that the first two drinks are consumed fairly rapidly, about a drink every 20-25 minutes.  Thereafter, it slows to about one every 35-45 minutes though I a number of times, I have averaged 1 an hour.  If I drink faster such as at parties then I tend to get drunk.\r\n\r\nWhen I do drink over an extended period, say over from a weekend afternoon to bedtime, my drink rate is much slower than normal and that is usually because I am doing other things at the same time.  On those occasions I normally donâ€™t get â€˜bladderedâ€™.\r\n\r\nAnother factor is food.  Eating before drinking is best followed by eating whilst drinking.  A lot of times though I eat after the drink.  What I do do is eat, whether I am drunk or not.  Rarely do I go to bed without food.  I also drink lots of water during the night.  I have always had this habit for as long as I can remember.\r\n\r\nNow with the fact that I am occasionally plastered, (Isnâ€™t it funny, how drinkers have so many ways to describe the level of drunkenness?) am rarely hung over, seem to have some limit, albeit higher than the daily recommended limit,  and can do without drink for a day or two, can I claim to have a drinking problem?', 'Can alcoholics have a limit?', 0, 'I suppose that the common view is that alcoholics drink until they fall over.  Is it true?  Can at least functional alcoholics have certain limits, because I seem to?', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'can-alcoholics-have-a-limit', '', '', '2005-10-12 21:41:31', '2005-10-12 20:41:31', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/blog/index.php/archives/9', 0),
(10, 1, '2005-10-07 13:19:19', '2005-10-07 12:19:19', 'Recently, before I started this blog, I had a dream.  I was in a dirty pair of underwear with nothing else on and in public!  Desperately trying to find some clothes to put on.  People where pointing at me and some were laughing, some looking at me in disgust.  Everywhere I turned, no one could or would help me. <!--more-->\r\n\r\nI suppose I was a bit worried about â€˜hanging out my dirty laundryâ€™.   It was also obvious I am scared of having to do it on my own.  This is going to be a personal battle, only I can change what is wrong.  However, I hope that there will be people on my side. I suppose there is always a danger that my real identity could be found and that could infringe on my life, particularly my work, but I will live with that.\r\n\r\nThis blog has several purposes to me.  It is to be record to look back on like a diary.  I also hope it will help anyone out there dealing with the same issues.  If it helps just one person come to terms with their situation, helps them on their personal journey, then it will be well worth it.\r\n\r\nThe most important reason I have for ignoring my instinct of â€˜hanging out the dirty laundryâ€™, is that this blog will be part of my spiritual routine.  Just thinking about what I am doing, analysing the reasons for my actions and reinforcing where I am going on a daily basis I suppose is like praying or meditating.  It also gives me a chance to do some mental exercise considering what is happening in the world, forming an opinion and writing about it.  I intend to blog on a daily basis as much as I can.', 'Hanging out the dirty laundry', 0, 'Recently, before I started this blog, I had a dream.  I was in a dirty pair of underwear with nothing else on and in public!  Desperately trying to find some clothes to put on.  People where pointing at me and some were laughing, some looking at me in disgust.  Everywhere I turned, no one could or would help me. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '10', '', '', '2005-10-12 21:43:57', '2005-10-12 20:43:57', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/10', 0),
(11, 1, '2005-10-08 22:10:17', '2005-10-08 21:10:17', 'Twice of note, I had limited success with giving up cigarettes.  Once I managed a week or so and the second time I gave up for over 3 weeks, a time when I had â€˜religionâ€™.  Iâ€™ll come back to the religion thing later but first, my gripe about â€˜nicotine replacement therapyâ€™.  There have been other times where I have used the useless therapy, which proved just as expensive as buying fags. <!--more--> \r\n\r\nWhat is the use if you cannot feel some benefit straight away?  Thank God, you can get in on the National Health, if you are willing or able to go to sessions during work time!  Imagine your bossâ€™ face when you say that you are off to your weekly â€˜stop smokingâ€™ clinic like you would for an appointment with the dentist.\r\n\r\nThis therapy is too restrictive.  You canâ€™t have any more that blah blah gums or use the inhalator more than etc etc.  The result, you are too bl**dy scared to overdose and so you actually end up craving tobacco.  When you do use this therapy, you do not satisfy the cravings completely.  Well I didnâ€™t.  If you smoke 30 to 40 fags a day, you are going to feel the craving!   This is one of the times when you know that some scientists are just out of touch!   Or, putting my suspicious hat on here, was it done so that the numerous world wide medical boards could approve the therapy?  \r\n\r\nIf I could replace cigarettes with something less risky and that very nearly satisfies the craving (just like smoking a slightly weaker cigarette) I could start to break the addition cues such as smoking after eating, first thing in the morning etc.  Thereafter, you can, my theory anyway, slowly reduce the level of nicotine intake at your own pace (a the hint for the scientists). In fact if you think about it, it would probably be more healthy to continue to suck on the inhalator for the rest of you life than to actually continue to smoke, how much worse can it be?  To quote the <a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/">National Institute For Clinical Excellence</a>\r\n \r\n<blockquote>â€˜Inhaled nicotine is strongly addictive. Therefore, stopping smoking results in craving and withdrawal symptoms. Nicotine itself is not a major primary cause of smoking-related disease, but it has marked effects on arterial tone. The main disease-causing element from smoking comes from ''tar'', a dark, viscous fluid formed from tobacco smoke, which contains at least 4,000 different chemicals, including over 50 known carcinogens and metabolic poisons.â€™</blockquote>\r\nI believe that the reason there is such a low success rate, 10% by some accounts, is that these issues are not considered when prescribing this therapy.  I think there is money to be made here and maybe help some of us poor souls.\r\n\r\nThere you go, one gripe of my chest for now.', 'Useless Nicotine Replacement Therapy', 0, 'Twice of note, I had limited success with giving up cigarettes.  Once I managed a week or so and the second time I gave up for over 3 weeks, a time when I had â€˜religionâ€™.  Iâ€™ll come back to the religion thing later but first, my gripe about â€˜nicotine replacement therapyâ€™.  There have been other times where I have used the useless therapy, which proved just as expensive as buying fags. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'this-is-a-test', '', '', '2005-10-12 21:44:52', '2005-10-12 20:44:52', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/11', 0),
(12, 1, '2005-10-10 22:21:41', '2005-10-10 21:21:41', 'I started smoking at 15 or 16 when I was still at school.  Mum had always smoked though she hasnâ€™t smoked now in ten years.  She finally bit the bullet one New Yearâ€™s day and hasnâ€™t touched one since then.  She wasnâ€™t the reason I smoked, I smoked because it was cool and I was grown up! <!--more-->Unfortunately, I started working soon after school and could afford my own.  I have previously tried to give up, it is the most expensive and â€˜waste of moneyâ€™ habit there is.  You canâ€™t even get high on the stuff!\r\n\r\nBrowsing the Internet I came across this site <a href="http://www.thecigarettecounter.com/">The Cigarette Counter</a>.  Now that''s what I''m talking about!  It makes so much more sense than the stupid <a href="/talking2myself/index.php/archives/11">NRT</a> I wrote about recently.  We smokers need solutions that allow us to wean ourselves of the filthy habit.  I know this is a cop out but, face it, â€˜cold turkeyâ€™ or NRT just does not work for the vast majority of us.  I think a rational way has a good a chance as any.  The body just doesnâ€™t like shock therapy!\r\n\r\nThere is a problem though is that I have never seen one of these locally.  I do not want to email them, I can just imagine the damn junk mail that will follow, but I will come up with a plan to simulate this idea and I will try it.  Damn, I might use my card when I have some credit on it (Maxed out at the moment).  But first, I have to deal with the strongest smoking cue I have, drinking.\r\n', 'The Cigarette Counter', 0, 'I started smoking at 15 or 16 when I was still at school.  Mum had always smoked though she hasnâ€™t smoked now in ten years.  She finally bit the bullet one New Yearâ€™s day and hasnâ€™t touched one since then.  She wasnâ€™t the reason I smoked, I smoked because it was cool and I was grown up! ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-cigarette-counter', '', '', '2005-10-12 22:28:05', '2005-10-12 21:28:05', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/12', 0),
(13, 1, '2005-10-11 22:37:49', '2005-10-11 21:37:49', 'In my hunt for tobacco related blogs to link to, I was not surprised to find quite a few documenting attempts to stop smoking.  Unfortunately not one was solely about giving up the dreaded drug.  Iâ€™d love to find a humourous account of the harrowing experience.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nMy search via technorati introduced me to the â€˜spam blogâ€™.  I understand that the term has been used for spammers posting comments to valid blogs but what I discovered is that there seems to be a few blogs that are constantly updated with the same material, most probably by some sort of automated system, which ensures they remain in the blog directories.  Nicotine therapies obviously are big business.  Is there no end to the lengths these people will go to gain eyeballs?\r\n\r\nAnyway, wading through the herbal remedies, replacement therapy and everything in between, I found out that Muslims during Ramadam give up not only food but the smokes as well.  I read an excellent <a href="http://bumming4inspiration.blogspot.com/2005/10/happy-meal-for-soul-mcmeaning-of-life.html">blog posting</a>  about this.  It got me thinking though that, maybe, there is a point to this.  Nothing can make you appreciate things a little bit more like abstention (absence makes the heart grow fonder). Of course, if I was one, I would take the opportunity give up smoking at this time but the fasting, I think, can must be good for the spirit. I suppose the most serious dieters would point out that your body would go into â€˜starvation modeâ€™ and store all available fat and water you eat outside the fasting period.  Christians are also supposed to give up something in Lent, though I suppose it is possible that originally, it was probably as strict as Ramadam.\r\n\r\nBut then this might be the point.  We have grown so accustomed to always having that out bodies do not have the chance to call on reserves and so we get fat and obese.  Far more important, I believe, is the spiritual thanksgiving (whether Muslim or Christian) that comes from doing without. Not being religious though, I think apart from appreciating these things we have, it also allows us to feel a connection to the millions that go without every day and not from choice.  Maybe then, we would not change the channel on the TV when we hear another appeal for help!\r\n', 'Ramadam and Cleansing', 0, 'In my hunt for tobacco related blogs to link to, I was not surprised to find quite a few documenting attempts to stop smoking.  Unfortunately not one was solely about giving up the dreaded drug.  Iâ€™d love to find a humourous account of the harrowing experience.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'ramadam-and-cleansing', '', '\nhttp://bumming4inspiration.blogspot.com/2005/10/happy-meal-for-soul-mcmeaning-of-life.html\n\n', '2005-10-17 22:40:12', '2005-10-17 21:40:12', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/13', 0),
(15, 1, '2005-10-13 22:53:10', '2005-10-13 21:53:10', 'Last night, I had a hell of a dream.  I was in a posh hotel bar on my own and these two guys, important looking guys came in, pointed at me and said something to two other guys, hard looking ba***ds, sitting on one of the other tables who promptly stood up, got up swearing at me and threw a packet of cigarettes at me.  <!--more-->I got up in a huff and rushed towards these guys ready and looking for a fight (I am bl**dy nuts at this time) and the next thing I know, I am in a back room and crushing heads and arms in the door as they tried to come in.  Next thing, a kid, someone I know, has pulled a ceiling tile and called me up so I climb up there, I obviously have locked the door because I put the ceiling tile back and am rushing about looking for a safe way out of the ceiling as I can hear these thugs looking for me below and this kid is trying to tell me something and I am constantly telling him to shut up in a hushed voice.\r\n\r\nAnyway, next thing I know, Iâ€™ve pulled up another ceiling tile and I have jumped into the hotel room of an old couple who get up shouting and screaming as I land on their bed and then, wait for it, Iâ€™ve torn a leg of a old oak or something like it table and guess what?  I go back in the bar holding the table leg and screaming right back at those thugs.  The look on their faces!  Then I woke up.\r\n\r\n Now I am not a violent man, last time I had a fight I was in primary school.  I rarely get cross enough to even contemplate lifting my hands but in this dream, but in this dream, I am out of totally out of control.\r\n\r\nI rarely remember dreams but this one is joining the list.   I have read dream interpretation books for ages, my mum is well into those, but I donâ€™t need a book to tell me what was on my mind. I have constantly telling myself that I have a fight on my hands and I want to beat it.  I have spent my life looking for ways out of the trouble I get myself into. Running away is my style and this dream means having to go back and deal with it.  Letâ€™s hope I can do it.\r\n', 'Fighting the demons', 0, 'Last night, I had a hell of a dream.  I was in a posh hotel bar on my own and these two guys, important looking guys came in, pointed at me and said something to two other guys, hard looking ba***ds, sitting on one of the other tables who promptly stood up, got up swearing at me and threw a packet of cigarettes at me. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'fighting-the-demons', '', '', '2005-10-20 22:58:57', '2005-10-20 21:58:57', '', 0, 'http://www.learning-mentors.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/15', 0),
(14, 1, '2005-10-09 22:04:01', '2005-10-09 21:04:01', 'Last night I got drunk.  I went to watch the England match (well done England) at the pub, had three pints during the game and came home.  I got angry at something my wife did but did not speak to her about it and instead went and got an eight pack.  <!--more-->By the time I went to bed I was drunk and had upset two of my kids.  This morning, I dealt with the issue that made me angry, apologised to the kids and then sat them down and explained what is going on in my life.  I did tell them about the problems â€“ drink, money, work and our strained marriage.  We sometimes think that kids donâ€™t see whatâ€™s going on but the usually know more then we think.\r\n\r\nIt is time to take stock now that I have tried over the past week to analyse the background to my problems.  I have always believed that striking a balance in life is probably the best way to achieve happiness.  The problem is that to break all the bad habits, ignore the stresses of life and concentrate on being content is a huge task and so we sometimes try to change one or two things but do make a concentrated effort to achieve balance.\r\n\r\nThe task I am setting is a huge one, slowly but surely I am going to go for it.  I need to reduce the drinking and the smoking, eventually giving it all up, get more exercise and do so on a regular basis and eat better.   Most of all, take some time out every day for myself to meditate about me and the world around me, some of those thoughts will be recorded here in this blog.  Over the next week, I will start to put together a schedule and start to take steps to contentment. \r\n\r\n', 'Stock-taking Time', 0, 'Last night I got drunk.  I went to watch the England match (well done England) at the pub, had three pints during the game and came home.  I got angry at something my wife did but did not speak to her about it and instead went and got an eight pack.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'stock-taking-time', '', '', '2005-10-12 22:48:09', '2005-10-12 21:48:09', '', 0, 'http://www.learning-mentors.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/14', 0),
(16, 1, '2005-10-20 22:18:23', '2005-10-20 21:18:23', 'No matter what I have said before, I am starting to realise that I am on a loser!  I cannot keep control of what I am doing. Tonight I am drunk again and no matter how I tried to say no, I went to the pub.  Damn it, why am I such an idiot?<!--more-->\r\n\r\nI donâ€™t care what they say, I am supposed to be in control of my life.  If I ever belive that my life is pre-ordained, then shoot me.  We are the result of our own actions and damn it, I have to get me some balls!\r\n', 'Can I beat this?', 0, 'No matter what I have said before, I am starting to realise that I am on a loser! I cannot keep control of what I am doing. Tonight I am drunk again and no matter how I tried to say no, I went to the pub. Damn it, why am I such an idiot?', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'can-i-beat-this', '', '', '2005-10-23 16:25:16', '2005-10-23 15:25:16', '', 0, 'http://www.learning-mentors.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/16', 0),
(17, 1, '2005-10-12 23:01:20', '2005-10-12 22:01:20', 'Abstention?  All of us men need some bad habits and I can think of many other things worse than drinking and smoking.  <!--more-->I want to give up smoking completely; itâ€™s a complete waste of time and money. But drinking?  All of my social life revolves around drinking.  My close associates, friends and family all drink socially.  Some, I suspect, are in the same situation as I am but we strive on the influence to socialise. Normally I am a shy person but under the influence, we can talk about anything, politics, religion and any other thing that catches our fancy.\r\n\r\nDonâ€™t get me wrong, I do know people who do not drink at all or drink moderately and let me say, most of them are BORING!  I remember the last time I gave up smoking and at the time, drinking wasnâ€™t an issue, I felt boring.\r\n\r\nI have this theory, of course, I have a few, that every male (women are from another planet, trust me) has a crutch or two or three, there are those who love cars, those whose football team wrings their pocket every week, those womanizers we all envy like hell and everything in-between.  Think about every man you know and each and every one of them has a habit of some sort that is detrimental to some aspect of his life.\r\n\r\nI am not going to con myself that I will be completely deprive myself of the lager, itâ€™s just not going to happen.  I donâ€™t know why but there is something about being able to relate to other people like that!   Another I know is that I am a â€˜people watcherâ€™.  I think itâ€™s got something to do with my artistic nature. I love watching people interact.  And there is no better place to see that but the pub where the defenses are a bit more relaxed. It inspires me to write.  Watch this space!', 'Alcohol Abstention - Not an  option!', 0, 'Abstention?  All of us men need some bad habits and I can think of many other things worse than drinking and smoking.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'alcohol-abstention-not-an-option', '', '', '2005-10-23 10:56:04', '2005-10-23 09:56:04', '', 0, 'http://www.learning-mentors.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/17', 0),
(25, 1, '2005-10-21 18:46:40', '2005-10-21 17:46:40', 'A couple of days ago, I have decided to grow my beard and keep my hair long as a visual reminder that I need to make a change in my life.  <!--more-->\r\n\r\nNot that it seems to have made much change to my habits so far.  I will keep it up until Christmas and see how it goes.  Not really in the mood for talking today so I''ll leave it at that.  But after reading this <a href="http://blog.vbsoft.org/pivot/entry.php?id=173">The Life of V Â» Beer</a>  I am not surprised that some of us keep drinking the golden liquid?\r\n\r\n', 'Changed Appearance not working', 0, 'A couple of days, I have decided to grow my beard and keep my hair long as a visual reminder that I need to make a change in my life. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'changed-appearance-not-working', '', '', '2005-10-31 19:04:12', '2005-10-31 18:04:12', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/25', 0),
(19, 1, '2005-10-14 12:01:20', '2005-10-14 11:01:20', 'Today seems to have been my day for seeing the results of a crazy and inefficient immigration/asylum system in the UK and I suspect all over Europe.  The last election was dogged by talk of immigration and asylum that drew attention from the things we in England should have been pressing the politicians about.  This paranoia about some 2% of the population is stupid!  If our emigrating citizens where being treated in the way we treat people coming to our shores, we would be in an uproar.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nAnyway, the news, this morning, reported the decision by the Asylum And Immigration Tribunal that Zimbabweans do face a risk of persecution if returned to Zimbabwe on failing an asylum claim.  If you are into such issues, the <a href="http://www.iaa.gov.uk/cg_determinations/country_guidelines/cg_list/aa_04507_2005_zimbabwe.pdf">decision</a> makes interesting reading.  Now this doesnâ€™t affect me directly as I am a citizen but I do know quite a few Zimbabweans who have had to face the asylum or the immigration system and let me tell you it sucks!\r\n\r\nIt is funny how until someone is directly affected by a law that they come to realise that sometimes we accept the Government is doing the best for us.  How many cases have there been where men have married foreign women and then found they canâ€™t get them into the country?  If an Englishman decides he wants to marry a young Thai or Philippine woman to spend the rest of his life with, why should the Government tell him he canâ€™t?  Yes, it may be a marriage of convenience, but arenâ€™t many marriages just that?\r\n\r\nOne of my friends is in love with someone has failed in their asylum case and is under the threat of deportation to Zimbabwe.  He has come face to face with the heart-acre, insecurity and sheer bureaucracy that is this system. Todayâ€™s decision should have been good news for the couple but an incident, this evening at the pub, displayed the frustration and insecurity these people have to live with on daily basis.  Until there is a clear description of what this decision means to these people, the uncertainty will continue to do their lives.  And because, basically, they are people with no rights with very little access to people who can defend them, they will continue to be a small, silent, suffering community hidden within our society.  Not a healthy situation!\r\n', 'Mad Asylum & Immigration Laws', 0, 'The last election was dogged by talk of immigration and asylum that drew attention from the things we in England should have been pressing the politicians about.  This paranoia about some 2% of the population is stupid!  If our emigrating citizens where being treated in the way we treat people coming to our shores, we would be in an uproar.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'mad-asylum-laws', '', '', '2005-10-23 12:02:50', '2005-10-23 11:02:50', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/19', 0),
(20, 1, '2005-10-15 12:51:15', '2005-10-15 11:51:15', 'A lady across the road once asked my wife how to get into fostering.  Apparently she thought that by sheer number of children that seemed to be in and out of our house, we were fostering.  But that is our house, not only do we have children of all sizes, shapes and races coming and going we have adults, African, West Indian, Asian, European and all sort of mixes doing the same.   Some people we see regularly, others only occasionally but ours is an open house.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThe guys at work have a nickname for my house;  The UNHCR (United Nations High Commission for Refugees).  Sometimes, when we want a break, my grandmotherâ€™s words that have been echoed by many people since, is that our house is blessed.  I believe it is.  My childrenâ€™s friends, my wifeâ€™s friends and my friends, family members all feel welcome in our â€˜not so tidyâ€™ abode.  We have never had to throw anyone out of our house. We have had heated debates and occasionally an argument but never have we had a fight!  Oh, yes, people have been banned where their behaviour warrants it.\r\n\r\nThe disadvantage for me is obviously whether the call is social or someone looking for a shoulder to cry on is inevitably alcohol is part of the proceedings.  \r\n\r\nThis evening was one of those impromptu party days.  My wifeâ€™s cousin came down from Scotland with a girlfriend and with the other visitors today, we had to light up the barbeque (I know summerâ€™s over but the weather was alright) to cook and we drank late into the night.  We had a sing along with the guitar and were introduced to some Scottish folk music.  Now, why should I give that up? ', 'A Blessed Home?', 0, 'A lady across the road once asked my wife how to get into fostering.  Apparently she thought that by sheer number of children that seemed to be in and out of our house, we were fostering.  But that is our house, not only do we have children of all sizes, shapes and races coming and going we have adults, African, West Indian, Asian, European and all sort of mixes doing the same.   Some people we see regularly, others only occasionally but ours is an open house.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'blessed-home', '', '', '2005-10-23 12:52:00', '2005-10-23 11:52:00', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/20', 0),
(21, 1, '2005-10-16 13:47:50', '2005-10-16 12:47:50', 'Looking back at this week and I can see I have not done very well, have I?  I only managed two days without drinking and another day with limited intake.  I canâ€™t even think about giving up the cigarettes until I get a handle on the drink.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nDiet wise, I have not even started to contemplate any changes.  If I am to start a regime, I need to be prepared and the lack of funds just means I have to eat what I can get.\r\n\r\nExercise wise I managed two sessions of Pilates on Monday and Tuesday but the other days I felt so tired that 6am wake up was not an option.   My plan had been to get back into exercise mode with Pilates this week and then add Tai-bo next week.  Though I feel a bit disappointed with the effort this week, I have to remember that sleep is just as important.  I managed a few early nights but I struggled to get to sleep especially on the days I did not or had only a few beers.  My mind just keeps going riot and whatever I do I find myself still awake a few hours later.\r\n\r\nI did mediate both on Monday and Tuesday before the exercise.  I am aiming for half an hour each day, early in the morning before the morning household rush.\r\n\r\nMt timetable in the morning should be\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>5.00 Wake up & have a cup of tea and a fag</li>\r\n	<li>5.30 Mediate</li>\r\n	<li>6.00 Start the morning rush by waking my eldest</li>\r\n	<li>6.01 An hour of exercise</li>\r\n	<li>7.00 Have a bath, shave and get my youngest ready for school</li>\r\n	<li>8.00 Breakfast for the kids</li>\r\n	<li>8.40 Drop the kids at school go to work.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nI need about 7 hours sleep, so working backwards, I should be in bed for 10pm.  I could get away with about half an hour.\r\n\r\nLetâ€™s see how I do next week.', 'Reviewing the week', 0, 'Looking back at this week and I can see I have not done very well, have I?  I only managed two days without drinking and another day with limited intake.  I canâ€™t even think about giving up the cigarettes until I get a handle on the drink.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'week-review1', '', '', '2005-10-23 13:48:51', '2005-10-23 12:48:51', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/21', 0);
