(22, 1, '2005-10-17 14:11:12', '2005-10-17 13:11:12', 'Despite feeling a little worse for wear yesterday, I forced myself to do stuff around the house to tire my self out.  If I spent the day recovering from the Saturday night festivities, I knew I would struggle to fall asleep.  So I cleaned the whole house except for the rooms and the kitchen and tidied up some stuff in the garden. I think my sleep pattern has not reverted to norm since our annual â€˜friends and familyâ€™ barbeque at the end of August.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThat did not help.  I did feel tired and worn out by 9.30 and was in bed for about 10, I then failed to get any sleep until past midnight. I used to have this system for sleep that worked very well in the past but is failing me miserably this time.  \r\n\r\nI usually lie on my back, breathe in deeply threw my nose and breathe out through my mouth until my natural reaction is to breathe in again.  I do this a couple of times with my eyes closed.  Next, starting with my toes I try and relax the muscles all the way to my face, you know, ankles, calf, thigh, bum, groin, stomach, lower back, upper back, chest, shoulders, upper arms, lower arms, fingers, neck, neck, face and then the brain.\r\n\r\nI canâ€™t seem to concentrate enough before half way, I either have to go to the toilet or my mind has wandered off thinking of work, home or on some sort of daydream. I drink a lot of water when I go to bed, it is a habit I have had for years, maybe as far back as the Seychelles when the nights can be hot and humid.  The disadvantage is if I do not go to sleep quickly, I will make several trips to the toilet.\r\n\r\nI have always thought what a waste of time, sleeping is.  I means, why canâ€™t the body repair itself and do itâ€™s housekeeping in an hour or two?  That way we get 22 hours a day.  I do recognise the need for a good nightâ€™s sleep though, the feeling of being tired all day is just horrible. So thereâ€™s another thing I have to work on in the next week or so. ', 'Sleep don''t come easy', 0, 'Despite feeling a little worse for wear yesterday, I forced myself to do stuff around the house to tire my self out.  If I spent the day recovering from the Saturday night festivities, I knew I would struggle to fall asleep. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'sleep-dont-come-easy', '', '', '2005-10-23 14:32:03', '2005-10-23 13:32:03', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/22', 0),
(23, 1, '2005-10-18 14:33:57', '2005-10-18 13:33:57', 'Fridayâ€™s incident with my friend and his asylum seeking girlfriend came back to haunt me again.  I found myself between two warring factions and I ended up feeling like I needed asylum. <!--more-->Anyway peace returned in the evening over a few cans of beer, though they were both worse for wear when they came round.\r\n\r\nOur system here leaves too many people vulnerable to unscrupulous people.  Whereas you can expect that if the authorities donâ€™t know about a person, e.g. an illegal immigrant, very little can be done to protect them, those who are known to the system should have more done to protect them.  In some instances, asylum seekers can get some help for accommodation and living expenses but when you consider the sheer numbers, it is the authoritiesâ€™ interests if these people are afforded help by friends and family who have some right to be here.  Many asylum seekers also know that if you are be supported by the system, there are two problems, one is that there is a vested interest by the authorities to get rid of you and secondly that should your claim fail, you have the greatest chance of being removed.\r\n\r\nThe problem is the whole process can take months and months and add in any appeals etc and you could be looking at a year.  For a family assisting another this puts a major strain on any resources they have access to.  Some of these families are successful asylum seekers who, in most cases, have low paid jobs and are struggling to make ends meet.  The prospective asylum seekers are not allowed to work but are expected for example, to travel to an immigration office and â€˜sign onâ€™ in some cases, every week.  Where is this money to come from?\r\n\r\nIt is from these pressures that abuse becomes an issue.  The asylum seeker is now under pressure to find means of support and there are many unscrupulous employers ready to take them on.  Yet, there are industries in this country that are crying out for labour and even law abiding businesses can find themselves skirting with the law in order to continue surviving.  Everyone in these cases is being criminalized by this system.\r\n\r\nIn other cases, the sheltering family takes advantage of this situation. Most of us have heard or read in the news a number of cases, where people have become virtually slaves.  Physical and mental abuse is not unheard of especially where children are concerned. \r\n\r\nWhilst you might argue that their situation here is better than what they are running from, it does not make it right!  We are a civilised and tolerant society that must face the fact no matter what we try and do, human nature will always result in people seeking shelter from those who would hurt them and we have a duty, as human beings, to afford them some help.  But leaving them in limbo with no means to ensure their safety and well-being is a recipe for disaster. ', 'Seeking Asylum', 0, 'Fridayâ€™s incident with my friend and his asylum seeking girlfriend came back to haunt me again.  I found myself between two warring factions and I ended up feeling like I needed asylum. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'seeking-asylum', '', '', '2005-10-23 15:26:07', '2005-10-23 14:26:07', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/23', 0),
(24, 1, '2005-10-19 16:14:47', '2005-10-19 15:14:47', 'When you want to discuss matters at work with work mates who live in different directions, the natural place, for me anyway, is the nearest watering hole.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThings at work have been very stressful lately.  We need more resources, the customers are hard to find and a lot of changes are in the air.  How we cope with this I think is by discussing strategies and brain storming with a pint or two.  There just isnâ€™t the time to do this at work.\r\n\r\nThe problem is though I might have or three pints, I get the taste and it is likely that I will drink a further two or three when I get home.  I cannot put my finger on it but I just canâ€™t seem to stop myself from getting those extra cans as I go in for my cigarettes.  I am trying to determine exactly how I feel when I want another drink, itâ€™s like being hungry but then again maybe I am hungry and that is acting like a prompt to get a drink.\r\n\r\nI usually have something to eat around 9.30am, earlier just doesnâ€™t work for me  though I try when I was on the low carb diet.  Itâ€™s just the hustle of cooking something in the morning that does my head in.  I have lunch around 2pm and so the longest time during the day when I do not eat is between lunch and dinner around 8pm.\r\n\r\nI am not a snack person but I have considered having another meal around 5pm.  However, all the food shops around my work close after lunch and that adds to my daily costs.  (Notice how the beer money is not considered!).   Just another thing to consider.', 'Pub Business Meetings', 0, 'When you want to discuss matters at work with work mates who live in different directions, the natural place, for me anyway, is the nearest watering hole.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'pub-business-meetings', '', '', '2005-10-23 16:15:30', '2005-10-23 15:15:30', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/24', 0),
(26, 1, '2005-10-22 11:04:15', '2005-10-22 10:04:15', 'I am not really in the mood to do any thinking today.  I feel so stressed and tired and all I really want is to eat and go to bed.', 'Just not in the mood', 0, 'I am not really in the mood to do any thinking today.  I feel so stressed and tired and all I really want is to eat and go to bed.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'just-not-in-the-mood', '', '', '2005-11-09 21:13:26', '2005-11-09 20:13:26', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/26', 0),
(56, 1, '2007-07-02 19:26:55', '2007-07-02 18:26:55', 'England, as many of us are aware, is now ''smoke free''.<!--more-->  The Governement has spent millions telling us this on billboards and advertising which really is not I want them using my tax money on but that''s another story.  I haven''t been able to smoke in a work building for years and so that''s nothing new.  I have always avoided smoking in restaurants, unless others are smoking, prefering to retire to the bar or even outside.  The pub ban is going to hurt especially in winter and maybe even this summer considering the ridiculous amount of rain - yes, I know it always rains in England - we have been having lately.  I must admit I haven''t paid much notice to the government funded campaign but now that it is in effect, I am seriously considering stopping smoking.   Many may say that it is the ban working, I beg to differ, I have been considering stopping for ages but the ban may be the catalyst to ensuring I stay not smoking because it is the pub that is always the hardest part.\r\n\r\nI haven''t been to the pub since the ban has come into effect but I suspect it will take some getting used to.  In October last year, I took my missus to Scotland for her birthday - just a long weekend - and I was surprised how people have got used to it.   Even a smoker said he preferred the pubs now they were non smoking.  I suspect by Christmas most of us smokers will think nothing of it.\r\n\r\nPoint is, it will be a major removal of temptation for ex-smokers, unless the smokers are congregated outside the front door of the pub.  Now might be the opportunity to give up this blasted dirty habit for once and for all.  I smoke and I hate it.  My decision is close.\r\n\r\nMay you find the balance.', 'Smoke Free England', 0, 'England, as many of us are aware, is now ''smoke free''', 'publish', '', '', '', 'smoke-free-england', '', '', '2007-07-02 19:26:55', '2007-07-02 18:26:55', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/56', 0),
(50, 1, '2007-07-02 18:20:25', '2007-07-02 17:20:25', '<a href="http://orwellsgrave.blogspot.com/2005/11/why-we-cant-prevent-cancer.html">Orwells20Grave3A20WHY20WE20CANT20PREVENT20CANCER</a>\r\n', 'Orwells20Grave3A20WHY20WE20CANT20PREVENT20CANCER', 0, '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'orwells20grave3a20why20we20cant20prevent20cancer', '', '', '2007-07-02 18:22:54', '2007-07-02 17:22:54', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/50', 0),
(32, 1, '2005-10-23 21:47:29', '2005-10-23 20:47:29', 'Had to work yesterday as the pressure is on.  It has been really for the nearly three years since my business partners and myself started our business.  We have just managed to keep our heads above water but the stress is telling.  <!--more-->If I consider how I used to enjoy my work before and how I feel about it now, I am not really surprised at how much I drink and smoke.  Replacing that release with something less harmful is where the trick lies I suppose.  Stress is one of the biggest excuses for having a drink, I know that.  You canâ€™t deny, that if you are a drinker, it works, I always feel relaxed after a few.  However, more than a few and depression at the situation can set in and I have had a few of those as well.\r\n\r\nAnyway, popped in the pub on the way home promising myself a single beer but met a acquaintance from Zimbabwe I havenâ€™t seen for  while and once the football was on the box, it was four beers before I left. Got home to find visitors and another couple was on the cards.  Makes me think that even social drinking is something that is going to be difficult controlling.  All in all felt OK, didn''t get depressed or anything.\r\n', 'Stress & Social Drinking', 0, 'Had to work yesterday as the pressure is on.  It has been really for the nearly three years since my business partners and myself started our business.  We have just managed to keep our heads above water but the stress is telling.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'stress-social-drinking', '', '', '2005-11-02 21:53:51', '2005-11-02 20:53:51', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/32', 0),
(33, 1, '2005-10-24 21:27:03', '2005-10-24 20:27:03', 'The riots made me sad.  After so many years of living together, a small number of people decide to undo all that work with a few nights of violence that left one person dead.  <!--more-->I am sad because wherever I have been in Birmingham over the last few years, I see children of all colours and creeds playing in the parks and on the streets.  For me that has been a hope for the future as even I release that the multi-culturalism of this great nation is being held back by the older generations who hold prejudices that many of us keep to ourselves.  I have always been of the opinion that if you can be as racist as you want but leave it at the door when you leave home.  If all of us acted on our prejudices and pet hates, we certainly would be living in a sad and scary world. \r\n\r\nThe children are the future not only of this country but of the whole world and hatred and stupidity like this does note help.  How are these children supposed to act at school on Monday after the press reports and the violence?  I am very sad.\r\n\r\nCan we really justify the damage done on the strength of what has yet to be proved?  Even if the rumours were true, do you blame a whole section of society for the actions of a few bad apples?  The only winners of the riots are the bigots that keep saying â€˜that multi-culturalism has not worked and that all immigrants should be deportedâ€™. I have seen working it working and let me tell you something; it is a beautiful thing to see. \r\n\r\nHere are a links to another thought of the riots.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://ardenforester.blogspot.com/2005/10/birmingham-riots.html">A View from Middle England: Birmingham Riots!</a>\r\n', 'The Lozells - Birmingham Riots', 0, 'The riots made me sad.  After so many years of living together, a small number of people decide to undo all that work with a few nights of violence that left one person dead.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-lozells-birmingham-riots', '', '\nhttp://ardenforester.blogspot.com/2005/10/birmingham-riots.html\n', '2005-11-02 21:29:23', '2005-11-02 20:29:23', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/33', 0),
(34, 1, '2005-10-25 22:01:00', '2005-10-25 21:01:00', 'After a single Guinness last night, I found it so difficult to sleep.  I read <a href="http://www.alertbutnotalarmed.com/text/on_the_wagon/">this blog </a>\r\nthat made me jealous.  <!--more-->Unfortunately for me, a drink less evening does not necessarily turn into a perfect day.  I always seem to have lots of aches and pains the next day that I canâ€™t explain.  Iâ€™m not going to the doctor until I have something to really complain about.  I am tied of feeling like I am wasting their time every time I go there.  I promised myself that I would visit the doctor only when I feel so unwell; I feel I am going to die.  So much for a health service.  Come back to this subject some other time.\r\n\r\nSleep is the thing that is avoiding me.  My wife was not pleased with my sleeping pattern as I disturbed her tossing and turning nearly all night long.  It is funny just how things keep popping into your head when you are trying to sleep.  My old routine just does not seem to be working at all.  No sooner have I banished work from my mind, another thing pops in and it can be about just about anything.  Sometimes I even try to tire myself out by doing lots of things around the house.  It hardly works. \r\n\r\nI have decided that I am going to research some sleep related stuff in the near future to see if I can detect a pattern. \r\n', 'Staying Awake', 0, 'After a single Guinness last night, I found it so difficult to sleep.  I read <a href="http://www.alertbutnotalarmed.com/text/on_the_wagon/">this blog </a>\r\nthat made me jealous. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'staying-awake', '', '\nhttp://www.alertbutnotalarmed.com/text/on_the_wagon', '2005-11-02 22:18:28', '2005-11-02 21:18:28', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/34', 0),
(36, 1, '2005-10-26 21:16:23', '2005-10-26 20:16:23', 'Feeling lazy again to really spend some time with this journal of mine.  Sometimes the hours just pass you by and if you have the internet at your disposal you pick up things like this <a href="http://www.livejournal.com/users/ethereal_dusk/57910.html">Thank you, Alcohol.</a>.  I hope I never have to feel this way.\r\n', 'Wanting to avoid that', 0, 'Feeling lazy again to really spend some time with this journal of mine.  Sometimes the hours just pass you by and if you have the internet at your disposal you pick up things like this <a href="http://www.livejournal.com/users/ethereal_dusk/57910.html">Thank you, Alcohol.</a>.  I hope I never have to feel this way.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'wanting-to-avoid-that', '', '\nhttp://www.livejournal.com/users/ethereal_dusk/57910.html', '2005-11-09 21:21:03', '2005-11-09 20:21:03', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/36', 0),
(55, 1, '2007-07-02 18:49:35', '2007-07-02 17:49:35', 'One year and eight months later, I have come full circle again.\r\n<!--more--> \r\nWhen I last updated this blog, we were going through the process of selling our business and I took the blog off line because I felt I could not keep it up with all the work and stress.  After all, after that I would be able to concentrate on sorting myself out.  Well it took until April to finalise the deal - all the time, maintaining my habits.  Now over a year later, I have full circle and realise that I have to do something.  So much has happened and I suspect I will talk about this missed period over the next few posts.   That is not to say that I have not been worried by the issues, it is just I keep putting it off until tomorrow and now, tomorrow has come.  Time to change is here.\r\n\r\nI have been here before, even before the time I set up the blog.  This really has to be the last time.  This is the time, the changes will be made and made permanent.  It is sad to think that at the springly age of forty two,  I am just as messed up as when I was twenty.  Oh yes, I have the house, the family and a reasonably well paid job but personally I feel unsatifisfied, uncontent.  I have to admit that change does not come easy for me, the change of job and work location (involving an extra two hours commute everyday) have not been followed by other changes that, maybe, I should have made at the time both externally and internally.\r\n\r\nBut change has to start somewhere, hence the revival of this blog and my <a href="http://songsofwords.mukudu.net/">poetry</a> site.  True the poetry is old but I have a stack of new stuff that I have to add.  I also intend to continue the <a href="http://ellisfamily.mukudu.net">genealogy and related stuff</a> I have been doing on and off for a couple of years.  The intention to do something more productive than drinking and smoking.  These sites are to be my spiritual healing, my praying and my emotional outlet.\r\n\r\nThere are other changes in the offing including moving house.\r\n\r\nBeing my first post in such a long time, this starts my commitment to spend a little time hopefully everyday to evaluate where I am going for the goal is noble - contentment.  My feeling about that has not changed since I wrote <a href="http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/about-this-blogpod/">this page</a>.\r\n\r\nLove and peace, may you find the balance.', 'Back Again', 0, 'One year and eight months later, I have come full circle again.', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'back-again', '', '', '2007-07-02 19:10:53', '2007-07-02 18:10:53', '', 0, 'http://www.mukudu.net/talking2myself/index.php/archives/55', 0),
